ental roles in the discovery, along with contributions by leading scholars who offer unparalleled insights into one of the most significant scientific breakthroughs of our time.This illuminating book features an introduction by Tilman Sauer and invaluable firsthand perspectives on the history and significance of the LIGO consortium by physicists Barry Barish and Kip Thorne. Theoretical physicist Alessandra Buonanno discusses the new possibilities opened by gravitational wave astronomy, and sociologist of science Harry Collins and historians of science Diana Kormos Buchwald, Daniel Kennefick, and Jürgen Renn provide further insights into the history of relativity and LIGO. The book closes with a contribution by philosopher Don Howard, who reflects on the significance of Einstein's theory for the philosophy of science.Edited by Jed Buchwald, Einstein Was Right is an authoritative and thought-provoking account of one of the most thrilling scientific discoveries of the modern age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGravitational waves. 7aSCIENCE / Physics / Relativity.2bisacsh  aCaltech.  aEinstein's miracle year.  aInterstellar movie.  aIsaac Newton.  aNewton.  aNewton's law.  aRai Weiss.  aVIRGO observatory.  aZeeman effect.  aannus mirabilis.  abig bang.  abinary merger.  abinary stars.  acompact binary merger.  acosmic expansion.  acosmic microwave background.  acosmology.  adark energy.  adark matter.  agravitational wave astronomy.  ainflation.  ainterferometer.  ainterferometric.  amagnetic field.  aneutron star merger.  aquantum mechanics.  asolar eclipse.  aspecial relativity.  atime travel.  aunified theory.  auniversal law of gravitation.  awormhole.1 aBarish, Barry C.1 aBarish, Barry C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator